  title: A Preface to a Poem Celebrating the An Family's Three Sons Passing the Civil Examination
  author: Lee Saeuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Jukgye was the son of Master Jingjae and now serves as Signatory of the Secretariat, a fellow examinees with me. Once he said to me: "My father and his two brothers rose to prominence through the civil examination and reached the rank of Chancellor. Now my three sons have all, by good fortune, succeeded in passing the examination as well. Surely this is Heaven's will. My ancestor, Minister Seongseong, had a grandson, Minister Jeongdang, whose three sons also passed the examination. How can I doubt that Heaven has blessed the An family so abundantly? Minister Seongseong served King Chungnyeol, established schools, and cultivated talent. His literary accomplishments were unparalleled in recent ages. Yet even so, three generations passed before his grandsons saw their success in the examinations—a delayed reward indeed. Though my father accumulated virtue and practiced righteousness, I have done little to inherit his legacy. Yet my sons have succeeded so swiftly. Is this not Heaven's work? Heaven rewards the virtuous and punishes the wicked, and none gains honor without merit. Therefore, the virtue of my ancestors must have moved Heaven's heart and blessed my descendants. Should we not spread this tale in verse to inspire future scholars?"

    Yet for a long time he did not ask for my brush. One day his second and third sons came and said: "Because our three brothers have passed the examination, the state has granted our mother a stipend and enfeoffed her as a noble householder. Should we remain silent and not celebrate this in verse? Such would be negligent. Moreover, the duty of sons is first to honor their parents. This is why we seek your words, Master."

    I replied: "Since King Gwangjong established the examinations, they have never ceased. How many fathers and sons, brothers after brothers, have passed together! I am too ill to investigate thoroughly. Seek out the elders, consult the histories, and bring me a record. I shall write a preface for you."

    Within days, the An family returned, saying: "We dare not search back to ancient times. We have gathered but sixteen families from King Chungnyeol onward, beginning with Han Jungchan of Cheongju. Though numerous, what good is mere quantity? We humbly ask your instruction."

    I said: "Prime Minister Kim Geun had three sons who passed the examination: Buil, Busik, and Bui. Chancellor Min Kyeong had five sons who passed: Ganggyun, Jikgyun, Guanggyun, Ingyun, and Yanggyun. Chancellor Im Yu had three sons: Gyeongseok, Gyeonggyeom, and Gyeongsunn. The late Minister of War Li Ho had three sons. Inspector Kim Taehyeon had three sons who passed: Gwangjcheol, Gwangjae, and Gwangjro.

    Among those you have gathered: The Han family of Cheongju produced Saegi, Saegyeom, and Po. The Park family of Hamyang gave us Jang, Ri, and Gyewon. The Park family of Jinnyang brought forth Ingan, Inji, and Inu. The Park family of Jukju produced Munhwa, Hyosu, and Songsaeng. The No family of Hwapyeong gave us Seungwan, Seungjjo, and Seungsin.

    Of those now known to all: The Kim family of Gimhae produced Dongyang, Gwangyun, and Gwangwon. The Park family of Miryang brought forth Mirryang, Daeyang, Samyang, and Gyeyang. The Yeom family of Gokseong gave us Gukbo, Heungbang, and Jeongsu. The Seong family of Changnyeong produced Seokrin, Seokyong, and Seokrinn. The Bae family of Heung'an gave us Jungbo, Jungseong, Jungyou, and Jungyun. The Yu family of Jeonju brought forth Geukgang, Geukseo, and Geukje. The U family of Dansan produced Hongsу, Honggang, and Hongdeuk. And there were others: the Yi family of Woleseong, the Heo family of Yangcheon, and the Seol family of Hoegol.

    Alas! This shows how beautifully the state nurtures virtue and custom, and how magnificent are the talents of our Three Kingdoms. Though not all excellence comes from the examination system, yet from its flourishing flows the vitality of a nation's government in such unmistakable measure.

    Our Eastern land existed in the age of Yao and Yu, but history does not record it, so we cannot investigate. When Zhou enfeoffed the Great Teacher Kija of the fallen Shang, our land began communication with China. Though enfeoffed, he was not made a subject—such was the respect shown to his Way and his preservation of Yao's and Yu's principles. The temple of the Great Teacher stands in Pyeongyang, and the state offers sacrifice with utmost reverence. Thus has the Great Teacher's influence on our people run deep.

    How could we compare this to the shallow influence of Sang Ki and Wang Rong? Yet even their service in encouraging the young was not without merit. Their glory and reputation stirred the age, making even the common folk admire the examination system and urge their children toward it. This may well have begun with these two. Through such gradual influence, every household came to study, until families saw three, even five sons pass together. Great indeed is the merit of the Sang and Wang families.

    Now that I write in praise of the An family, I also invoke the Sang and Wang families—for this follows the ancient custom of honoring those who first created what we now celebrate.

    Alas, when mortals achieve success, they often forget their roots. Is this not a mystery of the heart?

    Master Jingjae's name was Chuk, with the courtesy name Dangjji. Minister Jeongdang's name was Bo, with courtesy name Wonji. The Signatory's name was Jip. His sons are: the eldest, Jungon, now Commander of the Army Secretariat; the second, Gyeongryang, now Left Remonstrant; the third, Gyeonggong, now Vice Director of the Bureau of Rites; the youngest, Gyeonggeoм, now pursuing his studies for the examinations.

    Written in the fourth month of the Year of the Dragon.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'civil examination' (gwageo) was the primary system for recruiting state officials in medieval Korea, open theoretically to all educated men regardless of birth.
  - key: ''
    value: King Chungnyeol (r. 1274-1308) was a Goryeo king who reinforced Mongolian influence but also promoted education and Confucian learning.
  - key: ''
    value: Kija (Jizi) was a legendary sage who fled the fall of the Shang dynasty to Korea, establishing the first Korean kingdom; he represents the origin of Korean civilization and Confucian culture.
  - key: ''
    value: Sang Ki and Wang Rong were Tang dynasty officials credited with establishing or reforming examination systems in China; the author notes their influence came later than Korea's indigenous development of such systems through Kija's teachings.
